      Bridgewater
   =20
 =20

You could imagine three phases in the life of a wildly successful billionai=
re hedge fund manager. In Phase 1, before you become a wildly successful bi=
llionaire, you will have access to more or less accurate facts about the wo=
rld. =E2=80=8BYou=E2=80=99ll be motivated to find out true facts, because y=
ou are still trying to become successful, and you will succeed or fail base=
d on your ability to understand the world correctly. If you make a mistake,=
 you will lose money, and nobody will sugarcoat it or tell you that you are=
 a hidden genius. Of course it is hard, for anyone, to find out true facts =
and understand the world correctly, and you might not make it. But if you=
=C2=A0do=C2=A0become a wildly successful billionaire hedge fund manager, it=
=E2=80=99s because you were good at it, because you had an unusual skill fo=
r finding out and understanding the truth.
In Phase 2, after you become a wildly successful billionaire, your access t=
o information will change, in some good ways (you can call people and ask t=
hem questions and they will answer) but also in some bad ways (the people a=
round you will have a tendency to tell you what you want to hear). =E2=80=
=9CI think we should buy soybean futures,=E2=80=9D you will say, and your s=
ubordinates will say =E2=80=9Cgreat idea boss=E2=80=9D because you have a l=
ot of money and they hope you will pay them some of it. The combination of =
your money and your past success will make everyone defer to you in ways th=
at make you worse at your job; you will not get the spirited pushback and f=
rank debate and negative feedback that you got in your scrappier anonymous =
days.
But you got to where you are by being good at finding out true facts about =
the world, and this is an extremely well-known problem, so you will compens=
ate for it. You will hire people who are not cowed by you, who will tell yo=
u the truth and push back on bad ideas. You will encourage your subordinate=
s to be honest with you; you will reward them for principled disagreement; =
you will seek out contrary views and negative feedback; you will be comfort=
able with discomfort.
In Phase 3, after you have been a wildly successful billionaire for a while=
, that will stop being fun? Like:
=09If people constantly push back on you, and if your ideas are constantly =
tested by reality, that will keep you sharper and allow you to make more mo=
ney for longer, but it=E2=80=99s hard work.=09If people constantly tell you=
 that you=E2=80=99re great,=C2=A0you will lose your edge, but you will spen=
d your days coddled and happy and surrounded by praise.

At some point you won=E2=80=99t need to make more money. You will have less=
 need to be right, and more need to be told that you are right. You will ge=
t more comfortable with comfort.
But you are, still, the person who got to where you are by being good at fi=
nding out true facts about the world. So you might keep in place the=C2=A0t=
rappings=C2=A0of Phase 2. You will keep=C2=A0telling=C2=A0people =E2=80=9Cn=
o, I mean it, be ruthlessly honest with me, if my ideas are bad you have to=
 tell me.=E2=80=9D They will just understand that you=C2=A0mean=C2=A0someth=
ing different. =E2=80=9CBoss, you know me, and you know that I am ruthlessl=
y honest with you and would push back if your ideas were bad,=E2=80=9D they=
 will say. =E2=80=9CSo you can believe me when I say: This is the best idea=
 I have ever heard in my career.=E2=80=9D And then you give them a $50 mill=
ion bonus and they are happy and you are happy and it just doesn=E2=80=99t =
matter that much=C2=A0if your idea was, in fact, bad. Maybe you=E2=80=99ll =
lose money! But you have plenty of money. Why not=C2=A0trade some of it for=
 praise?
I do not think this is particularly scientific or anything. But it is strik=
ing to me that:
=09Pretty much every large investing firm talks, to some degree, about bein=
g a meritocracy of ideas, in which people push to find the truth without de=
ference to rank. Because you kind of can=E2=80=99t do the job any other way=
!=09Bridgewater Associates, the world=E2=80=99s largest hedge fund, talks a=
bout it vastly more=C2=A0than all the others, and in weirder ways, with com=
plex scorecards and iPad apps to rank employees=E2=80=99 contributions, wit=
h a culture of =E2=80=9Cradical transparency,=E2=80=9D with a carefully cul=
tivated list of management principles. And Ray Dalio, Bridgewater=E2=80=99s=
 founder,=C2=A0has published a book of those=C2=A0principles (called=C2=A0P=
rinciples), and does a ton of media about how committed he is to radical tr=
ansparency and also  mentoring Diddy.

One way to understand this is that, much more than his peer hedge fund lumi=
naries, Dalio really is committed to seeking out honest feedback, and given=
 his success he has had to build a complex and enormous system to solicit i=
t. Another way to understand it is that he=E2=80=99s not, and he has built =
that complex and enormous system to feel better about himself.
Rob Copeland=E2=80=99s book about Bridgewater,=C2=A0The Fund, is out today,=
 and oh man does it have a point of view! Copeland=E2=80=99s thesis is esse=
ntially that the =E2=80=9Cradical transparency=E2=80=9D stuff is fake and B=
ridgewater=C2=A0is a pure cult of personality around Dalio, that all of the=
 scorecards and iPad apps were just overcomplicated ways=C2=A0to measure wh=
o=C2=A0agreed with Dalio the most. (They have been scaled back a bit since=
=20
Dalio stepped down.)=C2=A0In the introduction, Copeland tells the story of =
Paul McDowell, who built a Bridgewater=C2=A0app for ranking employee =E2=80=
=9Cbelievability=E2=80=9D:
He asked top employees to rank one another on the notion of who was most tr=
usted to make decisions in a given subject matter, starting from the top. T=
he system began to work a bit dynamically. If a slew of Bridgewater executi=
ves gave an underling overall positive believability ratings, the subordina=
te=E2=80=99s own opinion would begin to carry more weight. McDowell began t=
o see how believability could be a way to identify talent across the hedge =
fund.
But Dalio objected:

One of his subordinates had just flagged for him a suspicious finding: two =
people inside Bridgewater =E2=80=94=C2=A0one in investment research, the ot=
her a lowly information technology grunt =E2=80=94=C2=A0had higher believab=
ility scores than Dalio himself. People were beginning to whisper about it.
McDowell explained to Dalio that this was a sign the system was working, th=
at Bridgewater was fishing out pockets of talent in its ranks =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0exactly as Dalio had asked him to do.
Dalio=E2=80=99s voice made no secret of his irritation. Why doesn=E2=80=99t=
 believability cascade=C2=A0from me?

And so McDowell =E2=80=9Cassigned an underling to go into the software and =
program a new rule=E2=80=9D
  [1]
:
Dalio himself would be the new baseline for believability in virtually all =
important categories. As the original, top-most believable person at Bridge=
water, Dalio=E2=80=99s rating was now numerically bulletproof to negative f=
eedback.
The book is full of stuff like this: Dalio would call a big=C2=A0meeting, s=
ome underling would say something to the effect of =E2=80=9Cbuddy this is a=
 cult and the Principles are nonsense,=E2=80=9D Dalio would turn to other u=
nderlings and say =E2=80=9Cdo you agree,=E2=80=9D the other underlings woul=
d say =E2=80=9Coh no boss definitely not=E2=80=9D in unison, and the object=
or would get shamed and fired. (One of these stories is  excerpted in New Y=
ork magazine today. And  Vanity Fair has an excerpt about some of Bridgewat=
er=E2=80=99s show trials, conducted by James Comey.)=C2=A0A system of radic=
al transparency in the service of making the boss feel good.
Copeland also reports that this applied=C2=A0to investing decisions. From a=
n excerpt that  ran in the New York Times this weekend:

With the hope of turning around the firm=E2=80=99s investment performance, =
members of the Circle of Trust put together a study of Mr. Dalio=E2=80=99s =
trades. They trawled deep into the Bridgewater archives for a history of Mr=
. Dalio=E2=80=99s individual investment ideas. The team ran the numbers onc=
e, then again, and again. The data had to be perfect. Then they sat down wi=
th Mr. Dalio, according to current and former employees who were present. (=
Lawyers for Mr. Dalio and Bridgewater said that no study was commissioned o=
f Mr. Dalio=E2=80=99s trades and that no meeting took place to discuss them=
.)
One young employee, hands shaking, handed over the results: The study showe=
d that Mr. Dalio had been wrong as much as he had been right.
Trading on his ideas lately was often akin to a coin flip.
The group sat quietly, nervously waiting for the Bridgewater founder=E2=80=
=99s response.
Mr. Dalio picked up the piece of paper, crumpled it into a ball and tossed =
it.

I have   written before about my =E2=80=9Cstylized model for thinking about=
 Bridgewater,=E2=80=9D which is =E2=80=9Cthat it is run by the computer wit=
h absolute logic and efficiency; in this model, the computer's main problem=
 is keeping the 1,500 human employees busy so that they don't interfere wit=
h its perfect rationality.=E2=80=9D This is not Copeland=E2=80=99s view =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0there is human discretion involved, and no perfectly rational c=
omputer =E2=80=94=C2=A0but there sure are a lot of distractions. Very littl=
e of the book is about Bridgewater=E2=80=99s investing; almost all of it is=
 about Bridgewater=E2=80=99s=C2=A0personnel=C2=A0infighting. I am not sure =
if that is a flaw of the book, or of Bridgewater.
  [2]
=C2=A0
Dalio disagrees with all of this, and=C2=A0wrote on LinkedIn:

The book should be taken for what it is, which is another one of those sens=
ational and inaccurate tabloid books written to sell books to people who li=
ke gossip. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0
Bridgewater obviously is not and was not as he describes it.=C2=A0If it wer=
e, it wouldn=E2=80=99t have had so many happy employees who have stayed so =
long (about one-third have been there for over 10 years) and it wouldn=E2=
=80=99t have such great client loyalty and longevity (the average client ha=
s been with Bridgewater for 12 years). So this book is more a sign of the t=
imes when bad journalism is more a fiction than a source of truth.

I guess the two things I would say=C2=A0are:
=09I am a person who likes gossip, and I liked the gossip here.=09If I were=
 in Dalio=E2=80=99s position, I would probably devote my time to creating c=
omplex pseudo-scientific=C2=A0systems to encourage my employees to praise m=
e.=C2=A0It sounds nice!


