      WeWork
   =20
 =20

One thing to say is that WeWork Inc. was a good idea. Is a good idea! In a =
world of startups and=C2=A0post-Covid flexible work, it makes sense for com=
panies to rent office space in units of less than =E2=80=9Ca whole floor fo=
r many years=E2=80=9D; in a world where people seek fulfillment at work, it=
 makes sense for companies to outsource office management to a company that=
 is cool. The extremely simple form of the WeWork business model =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cwe will rent a bunch of floors in offices for long terms, ma=
ke them look nice,=C2=A0sublease them by the desk and the month, collect a =
large spread and serve beer=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0is pretty good. It is=
=C2=A0risky:=C2=A0If demand for office space collapses all of a sudden, you=
r revenue (monthly desk rent) will drop a lot faster than your expenses (mu=
lti-year leases). But it=E2=80=99s a business that makes=C2=A0sense, and yo=
u could probably mitigate the risks. Like, don=E2=80=99t lease tons of spac=
e all at once, for instance: Sign only enough leases to support a conservat=
ive estimate of demand, so that you are reasonably safe in a downturn.
WeWork didn=E2=80=99t just do the opposite of that; WeWork was, like, the v=
ery most famous example in the world of a company that grew too fast while =
trying=C2=A0meet grandiose expectations. WeWork founder Adam Neumann styled=
 himself as a visionary whose company would =E2=80=9C encompass all aspects=
 of people=E2=80=99s lives=E2=80=9D; it would be a =E2=80=9C state of consc=
iousness=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9C the world=E2=80=99s first physical social n=
etwork.=E2=80=9D And then he met SoftBank Group Corp.=E2=80=99s Masayoshi S=
on, who =E2=80=9C appreciated how he was crazy=E2=80=94but thought that he =
needed to be crazier,=E2=80=9D and who invested billions of dollars in WeWo=
rk to fund its rapid growth. Neumann pushed for insane growth, Son pushed f=
or insane growth, billions of dollars went into insane growth, and the resu=
lt was that, by the time WeWork filed for an initial public offering=C2=A0i=
n 2019, it was somehow out of money and in danger of bankruptcy if it did n=
ot pull off the IPO. It   did not! Neumann was forced out in a recapitaliza=
tion that left SoftBank in charge, the company struggled along with smaller=
 ambitions, it went public, Covid happened, there was a   debt restructurin=
g this year, and   yesterday it filed for bankruptcy. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s  =
 Ellen Huet and Eliza Ronalds-Hannon write:

=E2=80=9CWeWork=E2=80=99s model was priced for growth, so it was purposely =
set up to lose money for years,=E2=80=9D according to Rett Wallace, CEO of =
Triton Research, who has analyzed the firm=E2=80=99s finances since its fir=
st public filings.
But =E2=80=9Cwhen the real estate market turned,=E2=80=9D amid interest rat=
e hikes and the pandemic=E2=80=99s disruption to work trends, =E2=80=9Cpric=
ing got worse, tenant churn was higher and occupancy was lower. And when a =
dynamite consumer proposition meets bad economics, the economics are going =
to win every time.=E2=80=9D

WeWork=E2=80=99s  announcement says that =E2=80=9Cit has commenced a compre=
hensive reorganization to strengthen its capital structure and financial pe=
rformance and best position the Company for future success=E2=80=9D:

WeWork has a deliberate and value maximizing lease rejection plan that is e=
xpected to position the company for operational and financial success. As p=
art of today=E2=80=99s filing, WeWork is requesting the ability to reject t=
he leases of certain locations, which are largely non-operational and all a=
ffected members have received advanced notice. =E2=80=A6
David Tolley, CEO of WeWork said, =E2=80=9CIt is the WeWork community that =
makes us successful. Our more than half-million members around the world tu=
rn to us for the best-in-class spaces, hospitality, and technology that our=
 2,500 dedicated employees and valued partners provide. WeWork has a strong=
 foundation, a dynamic business, and a bright future.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CNow is the time for us to pull the future forward by aggressively =
addressing our legacy leases and dramatically improving our balance sheet,=
=E2=80=9D Tolley continued.=C2=A0

Not that long ago, if the chief executive officer of WeWork was talking abo=
ut =E2=80=9Cpulling the future forward,=E2=80=9D he would have meant, like,=
 renting out office space on Mars. Now he just means shrinking.
Someone probably could have built, like, =E2=80=9CWeWork but rational.=E2=
=80=9D Grow more slowly in the late 2010s, become profitable, take a hit fr=
om Covid but survive by offering a product that is more appealing in a post=
-Covid world, but=C2=A0less=C2=A0of it. My question is: Would you rather ha=
ve built=C2=A0that=C2=A0product, or actual WeWork? Neumann, the founder of =
actual WeWork,   became a billionaire, and he hasn=E2=80=99t even had to ru=
n WeWork for years. The present value of WeWork=E2=80=99s=C2=A0planned, eno=
rmous, world-changing growth, measured by the price that Neumann extracted =
from SoftBank for those plans in the late=C2=A02010s, might well have been =
much greater than the expected value of actually running a sustainable prof=
itable version of WeWork.
The late 2010s were weird, man. If you were a founder with perfect foresigh=
t, and you had a fully informed choice between =E2=80=9Cgrow sustainably, m=
ake money, and have a profitable=C2=A0business that lasts for centuries=E2=
=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cgrow way too fast, get that sweet sweet SoftBank money,=
 and flame out extremely publicly in a couple of years,=E2=80=9D I think th=
at the objectively rational choice would still be to take that SoftBank mon=
ey? Neumann is so much richer than he would be if he had made different cho=
ices! WeWork has worked out poorly, as a business entity, and catastrophica=
lly,   as a SoftBank investment. But it worked out well for him.

