   =20
      Carry pool
   =20
 =20

A while back, when the takeover battle for Sculptor Capital Management Inc.=
 was heating up,   I wrote about the odd dynamics of a publicly traded hedg=
e fund firm. Most hedge fund firms are private, and=C2=A0traditionally=C2=
=A0the manager of a hedge fund =E2=80=94=C2=A0like, the=C2=A0person=C2=A0ma=
naging the hedge fund =E2=80=94=C2=A0gets paid roughly all of the fees that=
 the=C2=A0fund generates. If she takes her hedge fund management company pu=
blic, she has to share those fees with public shareholders. Or, I mean, in =
theory she does. In practice, she gets paid whatever the board of directors=
 wants to pay her, in a competitive marketplace for hedge fund management t=
alent. If that ends up being roughly 100% of the fees her funds pay, then t=
here=E2=80=99s not much left for shareholders. Arguably this was part of th=
e dynamic that made Sculptor an attractive asset: It was paying a lot of it=
s fees to its managers and not a lot to its shareholders, so if you bought =
all the shares of the company (cheap!) then you could make yourself the man=
ager (expensive!) and collect those fees yourself. There was an arbitrage.
To=C2=A0some=C2=A0extent, this is a general feature of public companies and=
 of principal/agent problems: Really=C2=A0any=C2=A0public-company chief exe=
cutive officer, with the right board of directors,=C2=A0could pay herself a=
ll of her company=E2=80=99s earnings and leave nothing for shareholders (un=
til a hostile acquirer came along to do the arbitrage). But that doesn=E2=
=80=99t really happen much. In part this is because hedge fund managers are=
 unusually insulated from the market for corporate control: Sculptor really=
 was able to fend off a bid from a rival hedge fund manager by arguing that=
 its current managers are essential to the business; a regular CEO who paid=
 herself all of the earnings might have a harder time doing that. But it=E2=
=80=99s also a feature of the competitive marketplace for top hedge fund ma=
nager pay: If you run your own big hedge fund and it is=C2=A0not=C2=A0a pub=
lic company, you can make a billion dollars a year, so a public hedge fund =
firm has to pay a lot to compete for talent. The market for ordinary public=
 company CEOs is different. Private ball bearings companies usually pay the=
ir executives less than public ones.
Meanwhile a lot of private equity firms and other alternative asset manager=
s=C2=A0are public companies and it works fine for them? With so many of the=
 big managers public, the market for private equity talent does assume that=
 the shareholders need to get paid too. I guess the going rate is, like, ar=
ound half of the fees go to the managers and the rest to the shareholders? =
Bloomberg=E2=80=99s   Sridhar Natarajan and Gillian Tan report that=C2=A0Go=
ldman Sachs Group Inc. is raising its=C2=A0employees=E2=80=99 take rate to =
compete with other alternative managers:

The changes instituted over the past several months will lift the share of =
profits available for investing teams directly responsible for the performa=
nce of Goldman=E2=80=99s alternative-investment funds, people familiar with=
 the matter said. The board has approved the shift, which applies to some e=
xisting vehicles as well as future funds, one of the people said.
The share of performance rewards, known as carried interest, usually gets d=
ivvied up between employees and the bank=E2=80=99s own accounts. Under the =
new structure, investing teams will receive 40% to 50% of the carry pool, t=
he person said. That=E2=80=99s up from 30% to 40% for many of the funds, a =
share that varies based on fund type and size.
Goldman, which oversees $267 billion in fee-earning alternative assets, is =
trying to bring compensation more in line with rival investment firms as it=
 moves toward third-party capital to fund its investing activities instead =
of relying on its own balance sheet. The shift could also help fend off fur=
ther defections to rivals. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0
At Carlyle Group Inc., the alternative-asset manager run by Goldman alum Ha=
rvey Schwartz, 45% of carried interest is set aside for investment professi=
onals, according to its filings.=C2=A0

Disclosure, I used to work at Goldman, though not managing alternative inve=
stments; I didn=E2=80=99t get any percentage of any carry. On the other han=
d, I learned that the informal rule of thumb for modeling the profitability=
 of a trade, to the bank, was to calculate the expected revenue and then de=
duct 50%: half of the revenue for the bank, half for the employees. So this=
 seems about right.

