  [2] Byrne Hobart wrote about the Times excerpt: =E2=80=9CThe least conspi=
ratorial view of Bridgewater is that they were mostly long bonds during an =
incredible bond bull market, and came up with a fantastic story. That doesn=
't seem to be the whole truth; even if very few people there make investmen=
t decisions, a lot of them do produce investment research, and if macro inv=
esting is tractable at all, there are probably returns to hoarding lots of =
smart people and paying them very well to relentlessly focus on predicting =
what's next for the global economy, or figuring out the second-, third-, an=
d nth-order impacts of some policy change. That story might have been overh=
yped at some point, and Bridgewater's culture is peculiar, but the true sto=
ry may be that a fund with a 99th percentile public profile got there with,=
 say, 75th percentile performance and 99.9th percentile weirdness.=E2=80=9D


