<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Bridgewater</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You could imagine three phases in the life of =
a wildly successful billionaire hedge fund manager. In Phase 1, <em>before<=
/em> you become a wildly successful billionaire, you will have access to mo=
re or less accurate facts about the world. =E2=80=8BYou=E2=80=99ll be motiv=
ated to find out true facts, because you are still trying to become success=
ful, and you will succeed or fail based on your ability to understand the w=
orld correctly. If you make a mistake, you will lose money, and nobody will=
 sugarcoat it or tell you that you are a hidden genius. Of course it is har=
d, for anyone, to find out true facts and understand the world correctly, a=
nd you might not make it. But if you=C2=A0<em>do=C2=A0</em>become a wildly =
successful billionaire hedge fund manager, it=E2=80=99s because you were go=
od at it, because you had an unusual skill for finding out and understandin=
g the truth.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In Phase 2, <em>after</em> you become a wildly=
 successful billionaire, your access to information will change, in some go=
od ways (you can call people and ask them questions and they will answer) b=
ut also in some bad ways (the people around you will have a tendency to tel=
l you what you want to hear). =E2=80=9CI think we should buy soybean future=
s,=E2=80=9D you will say, and your subordinates will say =E2=80=9Cgreat ide=
a boss=E2=80=9D because you have a lot of money and they hope you will pay =
them some of it. The combination of your money and your past success will m=
ake everyone defer to you in ways that make you worse at your job; you will=
 not get the spirited pushback and frank debate and negative feedback that =
you got in your scrappier anonymous days.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But you got to where you are by being good at =
finding out true facts about the world, and this is an extremely well-known=
 problem, so you will compensate for it. You will hire people who are not c=
owed by you, who will tell you the truth and push back on bad ideas. You wi=
ll encourage your subordinates to be honest with you; you will reward them =
for principled disagreement; you will seek out contrary views and negative =
feedback; you will be comfortable with discomfort.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In Phase 3, after you have been a wildly succe=
ssful billionaire for a while, that will stop being fun? Like:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If people constantly push back on you,=
 and if your ideas are constantly tested by reality, that will keep you sha=
rper and allow you to make more money for longer, but it=E2=80=99s hard wor=
k.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If people constantly tell you t=
hat you=E2=80=99re great,=C2=A0you will lose your edge, but you will spend =
your days coddled and happy and surrounded by praise.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At some point you won=E2=80=99t need to make m=
ore money. You will have less need to be right, and more need to be told th=
at you are right. You will get more comfortable with comfort.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But you are, still, the person who got to wher=
e you are by being good at finding out true facts about the world. So you m=
ight keep in place the=C2=A0<em>trappings=C2=A0</em>of Phase 2. You will ke=
ep=C2=A0<em>telling=C2=A0</em>people =E2=80=9Cno, I mean it, be ruthlessly =
honest with me, if my ideas are bad you have to tell me.=E2=80=9D They will=
 just understand that you=C2=A0<em>mean=C2=A0</em>something different. =E2=
=80=9CBoss, you know me, and you know that I am ruthlessly honest with you =
and would push back if your ideas were bad,=E2=80=9D they will say. =E2=80=
=9CSo you can believe me when I say: This is the best idea I have ever hear=
d in my career.=E2=80=9D And then you give them a $50 million bonus and the=
y are happy and you are happy and <em>it just doesn=E2=80=99t matter that m=
uch=C2=A0</em>if your idea was, in fact, bad. Maybe you=E2=80=99ll lose mon=
ey! But you have plenty of money. Why not=C2=A0trade some of it for praise?=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I do not think this is particularly scientific=
 or anything. But it is striking to me that:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Pretty much every large investing firm=
 talks, to some degree, about being a meritocracy of ideas, in which people=
 push to find the truth without deference to rank. Because you kind of can=
=E2=80=99t do the job any other way!</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px=
;">Bridgewater Associates, the world=E2=80=99s largest hedge fund, talks ab=
out it <em>vastly more=C2=A0</em>than all the others, and in weirder ways, =
with complex scorecards and iPad apps to rank employees=E2=80=99 contributi=
ons, with a culture of =E2=80=9Cradical transparency,=E2=80=9D with a caref=
ully cultivated list of management principles. And Ray Dalio, Bridgewater=
=E2=80=99s founder,=C2=A0has published a book of those=C2=A0principles (cal=
led=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33287990.=
258408/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucHJpbmNpcGxlcy5jb20v/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb61b98=
12" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"><em>Principles</em></a>), and does a ton of media about how co=
mmitted he is to radical transparency and also <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33287990.258408/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cueW91dHViZS5jb2=
0vd2F0Y2g_dj03cy00ZXpyV2pFUQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8b59048b" itemprop=3D=
"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> me=
ntoring Diddy</a>.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One way to understand this is that, much more =
than his peer hedge fund luminaries, Dalio really is committed to seeking o=
ut honest feedback, and given his success he has had to build a complex and=
 enormous system to solicit it. Another way to understand it is that he=E2=
=80=99s not, and he has built that complex and enormous system to feel bett=
er about himself.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Rob Copeland=E2=80=99s book about Bridgewater,=
=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33287990.258=
408/aHR0cHM6Ly91cy5tYWNtaWxsYW4uY29tL2Jvb2tzLzk3ODEyNTAyNzY5MzMvdGhlZnVuZA/=
607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBaaac81f2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"item=
scope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"><em>The Fund</em></a>, is out to=
day, and oh man does it have a point of view! Copeland=E2=80=99s thesis is =
essentially that the =E2=80=9Cradical transparency=E2=80=9D stuff is fake a=
nd Bridgewater=C2=A0is a pure cult of personality around Dalio, that all of=
 the scorecards and iPad apps were just overcomplicated ways=C2=A0to measur=
e who=C2=A0agreed with Dalio the most. (They have been scaled back a bit si=
nce <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33287990.25840=
8/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTAtMDQvZGFsa=
W8tZ2l2ZXMtdXAtY29udHJvbC1vZi1icmlkZ2V3YXRlci1pbi1maW5hbC1zdWNjZXNzaW9uLXN0=
ZXA_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTEwNzIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmN=
lPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMxMTA3JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cBbaa6aef6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">
Dalio stepped down</a>.)=C2=A0In the introduction, Copeland tells the story=
 of Paul McDowell, who built a Bridgewater=C2=A0app for ranking employee =
=E2=80=9Cbelievability=E2=80=9D:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">He asked top employees to rank one=
 another on the notion of who was most trusted to make decisions in a given=
 subject matter, starting from the top. The system began to work a bit dyna=
mically. If a slew of Bridgewater executives gave an underling overall posi=
tive believability ratings, the subordinate=E2=80=99s own opinion would beg=
in to carry more weight. McDowell began to see how believability could be a=
 way to identify talent across the hedge fund.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But Dalio objected:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One of his subordinates had just flagged for h=
im a suspicious finding: two people inside Bridgewater =E2=80=94=C2=A0one i=
n investment research, the other a lowly information technology grunt =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0had higher believability scores than Dalio himself. People were=
 beginning to whisper about it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">McDowell explained to Dalio that this was a si=
gn the system was working, that Bridgewater was fishing out pockets of tale=
nt in its ranks =E2=80=94=C2=A0exactly as Dalio had asked him to do.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Dalio=E2=80=99s voice made no secret of his ir=
ritation. Why doesn=E2=80=99t believability cascade=C2=A0<em>from me</em>?<=
/p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so McDowell =E2=80=9Cassigned an underling=
 to go into the software and program a new rule=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"footnot=
e-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; =
display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Dalio himself would be the new bas=
eline for believability in virtually all important categories. As the origi=
nal, top-most believable person at Bridgewater, Dalio=E2=80=99s rating was =
now numerically bulletproof to negative feedback.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The book is full of stuff like this: Dalio wou=
ld call a big=C2=A0meeting, some underling would say something to the effec=
t of =E2=80=9Cbuddy this is a cult and the Principles are nonsense,=E2=80=
=9D Dalio would turn to other underlings and say =E2=80=9Cdo you agree,=E2=
=80=9D the other underlings would say =E2=80=9Coh no boss definitely not=E2=
=80=9D in unison, and the objector would get shamed and fired. (One of thes=
e stories is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33287=
990.258408/aHR0cHM6Ly9ueW1hZy5jb20vaW50ZWxsaWdlbmNlci9hcnRpY2xlL3JheS1kYWxp=
by1yb2ItY29wZWxhbmQtdGhlLWZ1bmQtYm9vay1leGNlcnB0Lmh0bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cBbf5168e7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;"> excerpted in New York magazine today</a>. And <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33287990.258408/aHR0cH=
M6Ly93d3cudmFuaXR5ZmFpci5jb20vbmV3cy8yMDIzLzExL2phbWVzLWNvbWV5LWRhbGlvLWJya=
WRnZXdhdGVyLXRoZS1mdW5k/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBbb57a0ba" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Vanity =
Fair has an excerpt</a> about some of Bridgewater=E2=80=99s show trials, co=
nducted by James Comey.)=C2=A0A system of radical transparency in the servi=
ce of making the boss feel good.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Copeland also reports that this applied=C2=A0t=
o investing decisions. From an excerpt that <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/33287990.258408/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0aW1lcy5jb20vM=
jAyMy8xMS8wMS9idXNpbmVzcy9ob3ctZG9lcy10aGUtd29ybGRzLWxhcmdlc3QtaGVkZ2UtZnVu=
ZC1yZWFsbHktbWFrZS1pdHMtbW9uZXkuaHRtbD9zZWFyY2hSZXN1bHRQb3NpdGlvbj0x/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cBcf8b828a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> ran in the New York Times this weeken=
d</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">With the hope of turning around the firm=E2=80=
=99s investment performance, members of the Circle of Trust put together a =
study of Mr. Dalio=E2=80=99s trades. They trawled deep into the Bridgewater=
 archives for a history of Mr. Dalio=E2=80=99s individual investment ideas.=
 The team ran the numbers once, then again, and again. The data had to be p=
erfect. Then they sat down with Mr. Dalio, according to current and former =
employees who were present. (Lawyers for Mr. Dalio and Bridgewater said tha=
t no study was commissioned of Mr. Dalio=E2=80=99s trades and that no meeti=
ng took place to discuss them.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One young employee, hands shaking, handed over=
 the results: The study showed that Mr. Dalio had been wrong as much as he =
had been right.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Trading on his ideas lately was often akin to =
a coin flip.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The group sat quietly, nervously waiting for t=
he Bridgewater founder=E2=80=99s response.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mr. Dalio picked up the piece of paper, crumpl=
ed it into a ball and tossed it.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I have <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/33287990.258408/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGlua=
W9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTYtMDItMDUvYnJpZGdld2F0ZXItcy1ib3NzZXMtYXJlLWZpZ2h0aW5n=
LW92ZXItc29tZXRoaW5nP2NtcGlkPUJCRDExMDcyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1=
haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMTEwNyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW=
9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB03b1b22e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  written before</a=
> about my =E2=80=9Cstylized model for thinking about Bridgewater,=E2=80=9D=
 which is =E2=80=9Cthat it is run by the computer with absolute logic and e=
fficiency; in this model, the computer's main problem is keeping the 1,500 =
human employees busy so that they don't interfere with its perfect rational=
ity.=E2=80=9D This is not Copeland=E2=80=99s view =E2=80=94=C2=A0there is h=
uman discretion involved, and no perfectly rational computer =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0but there sure are a lot of distractions. Very little of the book is abo=
ut Bridgewater=E2=80=99s <em>investing</em>; almost all of it is about Brid=
gewater=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<em>personnel=C2=A0</em>infighting. I am not sure if=
 that is a flaw of the book, or of Bridgewater.<a class=3D"footnote-index" =
href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: =
inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Dalio disagrees with all of this, and=C2=A0<a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33287990.258408/aHR0c=
HM6Ly93d3cubGlua2VkaW4uY29tL3Bvc3RzL3JheWRhbGlvX2ktd2FzLWFza2VkLXdoYXQtaS10=
aGluay1hYm91dC10aGUtdGFibG9pZC1hY3Rpdml0eS03MTI3NDM5MjQwMDEwODI5ODI0LUFab3I=
vP3V0bV9zb3VyY2U9c2hhcmUmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1tZW1iZXJfZGVza3RvcCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ2=
49bmV3c2xldHRlcl9heGlvc21hcmtldHMmc3RyZWFtPWJ1c2luZXNz/607f07ceef4b8524a319=
a23cB7229dbea" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bl=
ank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; ba=
ckground-color: #ccc;">wrote on LinkedIn</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The book should be taken for what it is, which=
 is another one of those sensational and inaccurate tabloid books written t=
o sell books to people who like gossip. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bridgewater obviously is not and was not as he=
 describes it.=C2=A0If it were, it wouldn=E2=80=99t have had so many happy =
employees who have stayed so long (about one-third have been there for over=
 10 years) and it wouldn=E2=80=99t have such great client loyalty and longe=
vity (the average client has been with Bridgewater for 12 years). So this b=
ook is more a sign of the times when bad journalism is more a fiction than =
a source of truth.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I guess the two things I would say=C2=A0are:</=
p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">I am a person who likes gossip, and I=
 liked the gossip here.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If I were =
