<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One thing to say is that WeWork Inc. was a goo=
d idea. Is a good idea! In a world of startups and=C2=A0post-Covid flexible=
 work, it makes sense for companies to rent office space in units of less t=
han =E2=80=9Ca whole floor for many years=E2=80=9D; in a world where people=
 seek fulfillment at work, it makes sense for companies to outsource office=
 management to a company that is cool. The extremely simple form of the WeW=
ork business model =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cwe will rent a bunch of floors i=
n offices for long terms, make them look nice,=C2=A0sublease them by the de=
sk and the month, collect a large spread and serve beer=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0is pretty good. It is=C2=A0<em>risky:=C2=A0</em>If demand for office =
space collapses all of a sudden, your revenue (monthly desk rent) will drop=
 a lot faster than your expenses (multi-year leases). But it=E2=80=99s a bu=
siness that makes=C2=A0sense, and you could probably mitigate the risks. Li=
ke, don=E2=80=99t lease tons of space all at once, for instance: Sign only =
enough leases to support a conservative estimate of demand, so that you are=
 reasonably safe in a downturn.</p>
