G1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMxMTA3JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0=
dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB83c99471" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  I wrote about</a> the odd=
 dynamics of a publicly traded hedge fund firm. Most hedge fund firms are p=
rivate, and=C2=A0traditionally=C2=A0the manager of a hedge fund =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0like, the=C2=A0<em>person=C2=A0</em>managing the hedge fund =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0gets paid roughly all of the fees that the=C2=A0fund generates. If sh=
e takes her hedge fund management company public, she has to share those fe=
es with public shareholders. Or, I mean, in theory she does. In practice, s=
he gets paid whatever the board of directors wants to pay her, in a competi=
tive marketplace for hedge fund management talent. If that ends up being ro=
ughly 100% of the fees her funds pay, then there=E2=80=99s not much left fo=
r shareholders. Arguably this was part of the dynamic that made Sculptor an=
 attractive asset: It was paying a lot of its fees to its managers and not =
a lot to its shareholders, so if you bought all the shares of the company (=
cheap!) then you could make yourself the manager (expensive!) and collect t=
hose fees yourself. There was an arbitrage.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To=C2=A0<em>some=C2=A0</em>extent, this is a g=
eneral feature of public companies and of principal/agent problems: Really=
=C2=A0<em>any=C2=A0</em>public-company chief executive officer, with the ri=
ght board of directors,=C2=A0could pay herself all of her company=E2=80=99s=
 earnings and leave nothing for shareholders (until a hostile acquirer came=
 along to do the arbitrage). But that doesn=E2=80=99t really happen much. I=
n part this is because hedge fund managers are unusually insulated from the=
 market for corporate control: Sculptor really was able to fend off a bid f=
rom a rival hedge fund manager by arguing that its current managers are ess=
ential to the business; a regular CEO who paid herself all of the earnings =
might have a harder time doing that. But it=E2=80=99s also a feature of the=
 competitive marketplace for top hedge fund manager pay: If you run your ow=
n big hedge fund and it is=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>a public company, you can=
 make a billion dollars a year, so a public hedge fund firm has to pay a lo=
t to compete for talent. The market for ordinary public company CEOs is dif=
ferent. Private ball bearings companies usually pay their executives <em>le=
ss</em> than public ones.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile a lot of private equity firms and ot=
her alternative asset managers=C2=A0are public companies and it works fine =
for them? With so many of the big managers public, the market for private e=
quity talent does assume that the shareholders need to get paid too. I gues=
s the going rate is, like, around half of the fees go to the managers and t=
he rest to the shareholders? Bloomberg=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33287990.258408/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJn=
LmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTEtMDYvZ29sZG1hbi1ib29zdHMtcGF5LWluY2VudGl=
2ZXMtZm9yLXJhaW5tYWtlcnMtaW4tYXNzZXQtbWFuYWdlbWVudD9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMTA3MjNfTU=
9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVyb=
T0yMzExMDcmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3974161=
5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">  Sridhar Natarajan and Gillian Tan report</a> that=C2=A0Goldm=
an Sachs Group Inc. is raising its=C2=A0employees=E2=80=99 take rate to com=
pete with other alternative managers:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The changes instituted over the past several m=
onths will lift the share of profits available for investing teams directly=
 responsible for the performance of Goldman=E2=80=99s alternative-investmen=
t funds, people familiar with the matter said. The board has approved the s=
hift, which applies to some existing vehicles as well as future funds, one =
of the people said.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The share of performance rewards, known as car=
ried interest, usually gets divvied up between employees and the bank=E2=80=
=99s own accounts. Under the new structure, investing teams will receive 40=
% to 50% of the carry pool, the person said. That=E2=80=99s up from 30% to =
40% for many of the funds, a share that varies based on fund type and size.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Goldman, which oversees $267 billion in fee-ea=
rning alternative assets, is trying to bring compensation more in line with=
 rival investment firms as it moves toward third-party capital to fund its =
investing activities instead of relying on its own balance sheet. The shift=
 could also help fend off further defections to rivals. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At Carlyle Group Inc., the alternative-asset m=
anager run by Goldman alum Harvey Schwartz, 45% of carried interest is set =
aside for investment professionals, according to its filings.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Disclosure, I used to work at Goldman, though =
not managing alternative investments; I didn=E2=80=99t get any percentage o=
f any carry. On the other hand, I learned that the informal rule of thumb f=
or modeling the profitability of a trade, to the bank, was to calculate the=
 expected revenue and then deduct 50%: half of the revenue for the bank, ha=
lf for the employees. So this seems about right.</p>
